<TEXT>
a state legislative election today between a 
former ku klux klan leader and a republican backed by former 
president reagan and president bush has focused international 
attention on a new orleans suburb 
poll commissioners reported a good turnout early today and a 
registrar predicted a record number of voters would cast their 
ballots in the race between former ku klux klan grand wizard david 
duke and his opponent john treen 
for nearly a month duke 38 and treen 63 have campaigned to 
represent the legislative district in metairie a nearly allwhite 
suburb with about 21000 voters 
the most recent polls conducted last week indicated the men 
were neck and neck an unusually large number of voters would not 
reveal their candidate of choice pollster joe walker said 
ive never seen anything like this in my life im 70 years 
old said jefferson parish registrar sam altobello we should 
have a hell of a turnout 
voter registration ended more than three weeks ago but altobello 
said even people outside the district have called to ask if they can 
register 
they all want to vote for one man altobello said one lady 
called yesterday and said if i cant vote for him im going to 
pray for him i know whos going to win but im not going to say 
altobello said a record 80 percent of voters could end up at the 
polls the 1988 presidential race drew 77 percent polls open at 6 
am and close at 8 pm 
of the 21457 people eligible to vote 52 are black 76 are 
registered as other and the rest more than 99 percent are 
white he said 
duke led a field of seven candidates with 33 percent of the vote 
in the jan 21 primary treen had 19 percent 
both men are running as republicans which drew the republican 
national committee into the campaign because it feared a duke 
victory would harm the gops image 
in an unprecedented move for a local race president bush and 
former president reagan endorsed treen earlier this week while 
neither mentioned duke 
the race also attracted international attention with reporters 
from british dutch french west german and other foreign 
newspapers covering the election 
dukes candidacy seems to confirm everyones perception about 
the south were going to look into it to see if thats true said 
john cassidy chief american correspondent for the sunday times of 
london 
under louisianas open primary system the top two votegetters 
in a primary regardless of party face each other in the runoff 
the seat opened when metairies representative was elected to a 
judgeship 
duke who ran as a democrat in the 1988 presidential primary 
switched his registration a few days before qualifying for the house 
race treen is a longtime republican whose brother dave served 
from 1980 to 1984 as louisiana governor 
duke left the klan in 1980 when another kkk leader accused him 
of selling secret membership rolls he then started the national 
association for the advancement of white people which duke says 
works for civil rights for everyone 
on friday duke spent the final hours before the election 
defending himself against accusations that he is still an associate 
of rightwing extremists 
hes spreading nazi venom across the united states treen 
said 
not only am i not a nazi but i condemn any sort of 
totalitarianism duke said i repudiate anybody or any group 
that advocates racial hatred or violence against anyone 
former american nazi leader ralph p forbes was hired to manage 
dukes populist party presidential campaign in 1988 and was paid at 
least 22000 for his work according to campaign finance reports 
quoted in fridays editions of the timespicayune newspaper 
the ralph forbes factor in this election is only the tip of the 
iceberg said treen 
</TEXT>
