<TEXT>
more than 100 blacks detained 
without charge remained on a hunger strike today attorneys said 
and a human rights group claimed that police have detained more 
people 
in johannesburg today 300 blacks chanted sang songs and danced 
as they waved placards and handed out leaflets demanding the release 
of all detainees 
about 300 detainees many held since a state of emergency was 
declared 1986 began a hunger strike three weeks ago demanding they 
be freed or tried 
more than 20 were hospitalized prompting law and order minister 
adriaan vlok to meet with lawyers clergymen and relatives of 
detainees during the week for the first time getting information 
other than that supplied by his policemen on why certain people are 
considered a danger to the community 
vlok said he would free a substantial number of detainees in 
the next two weeks he said most of those on hunger strike at 
least 275 suspended their protest thursday and friday 
but attorneys for more than 123 detainees held in westville 
prison in durban and about 30 in east londons fort glamorgan prison 
said their clients still are fasting those fasts began during the 
past week and the attorneys were not in the groups that met vlok 
police also confirmed that some detainees at fort glamorgan were on 
a hunger strike 
a spokesman for vlok brig leon mellett was quoted today by the 
citizen a progovernment newspaper as saying as far as i am 
concerned the matter of the hunger strike and the detainees 
involved is now something of the past and im not prepared to say 
anymore 
however a johannesburg group called the human rights commission 
said today the hunger strike continues at prisons around the 
country this highlights the fact that the detention crisis is not 
over even this week more people have been detained under the state 
of emergency it gave no figure for new detainees 
vlok has said people are released and detained every day 
monitoring groups say more than 30000 people almost all black 
have been held at some time during the two years and eight months of 
the emergency 
vlok told parliament on friday that on jan 9 there were 884 
detainees who had been held at least 30 days he is required by law 
to make periodic reports to parliament but he never gives 
uptodate figures last week he said there were less than 1000 
detainees 
in the past week at least 30 people have been freed from 
detention some of them hunger strikers officials did not say how 
many new detentions occurred 
in downtown johannesburg today about 300 blacks chanted sang 
songs and danced as they waved placards and handed out leaflets 
calling for the release of all detainees 
