<TEXT>
fishermen rescued fumio niwa from rough waters 
tonight maritime officials said almost 12 hours after the 
adventurer abandoned his attempt to become the first person to cross 
the pacific alone in a balloon 
the 38yearold balloonist was in good condition after suffering 
a severe bout of seasickness said his spokesman toshiaki oguri 
niwa was picked up in generally the same area where he came down 
this morning 400 miles off the coast of minami torishima an island 
1550 miles southeast of tokyo said oguri and the maritime defense 
force 
after his heliumfilled balloon landed in the water at 1116 
am niwa immediately separated his gondola from the balloons 
tentacles and bobbed around in the pacific ocean awaiting rescue 
oguri said he communicated with niwa by radio on the 59ton no 1 
yasueimaru he said he did not know the destination of the fishing 
boat which also is lugging the gondola which is six foot in 
diameter 
this afternoon niwa suffered severe sickness from the rough sea 
but recovered by the time he was rescued said kenji fukawa another 
spokesman 
niwa at one point opened a window at the top of his globeshaped 
capsule to get fresh air to combat the seasickness he also shone a 
beam out into the open sea with a flashlight after dark to help 
rescuers locate him fukawa said 
the fishing boat was guided to the site by one of two p3c patrol 
planes deployed by the self defense force the other one flew over 
niwas gondola to monitor his position 
attempts to rescue niwa in a seaplane failed the defense force 
this afternoon sent a us1 seaplane to the scene but it returned to 
base with engine problems a second us1 proved useless because it 
arrived after dark 
the fishing boat initially was delayed by strong winds of 30 mph 
which later diminished 
the balloonist took off wednesday from his hometown of yokohama 
near tokyo originally planning to reach san diego yokohamas 
sister city in about four days by hitching a ride on the 
highaltitude jet stream winds that generally blow west to east 
but since his departure the winds have blown north toward 
alaska forcing niwa to stay at a low altitude later he tried and 
failed to reach the jet stream said hiroaki tanaka another project 
spokesman 
niwa an experienced balloonist quit his job with a computer 
firm three months ago to prepare for the journey 
in 1981 four balloonists successfully crossed the pacific ocean 
by balloon for the first time no one has traveled the distance 
alone 
