<TEXT>
afghan guerrilla groups based in this 
country today nominated a moderate as president and a hardliner as 
prime minister for an interim government they hope will soon take 
power in their homeland 
mohammad nabi mohammadi was nominated as president and ahmad shah 
as prime minister according to a statement in english by council 
spokesman rab rasool sayyaf in earlier impromptu remarks to 
reporters he had said the two men had been approved for the 
positions however his written statement said their formal approval 
by the council was in fact expected sunday 
mohammadi who leads the moderate guerrilla faction known as 
harakatiinqilabiislami was earlier named president of the 
council itself 
his group was one of the largest guerrilla factions at the start 
of the civil war but it has since dwindled for lack of 
organization it has never received the amount of external support 
from the united states pakistan and other countries that the 
powerful hardline groups do 
shah a useducated engineer is a top political officer in the 
hardline ittehadiislami guerrilla group his group is the weakest 
of four fundamentalist pakistanibased guerrilla factions 
he was designated in early 1988 as prime minister of a guerrilla 
government that never became functional 
the nearly 400 council delegates cheered allahoakbar god 
is great when the nominations were announced indicating sundays 
vote will be a formality 
the consultative council or shura started its meetings in 
islamabad on feb 10 to form what its leaders say will be the future 
government of afghanistan 
the moslem guerrilla forces and many western diplomats say the 
marxist government of president najib based in kabul will soon 
fall now that soviet troops have withdrawn from afghanistan najib 
says his troops can hold on without the soviet soldiers 
the council spokesman said mohammadi will serve by virtue of 
being president as head of the presidium that ruling body will 
consist of a leader of each of the seven factions in the 
pakistanibased guerrilla alliance 
the president will be appointed for eight months the spokesman 
said at a news briefing today 
the prime minister and president will jointly present a list of 
proposed cabinet ministers to the council sunday the final day of 
the council session sayyaf said 
he added that an elected council will be formed within six 
months but he gave no details of those elections he said the new 
council will in turn name a president and ratify the interim cabinet 
the council had been bogged down over differences on 
powersharing between the seven groups in the pakistanibased 
resistance iranianbased guerrilla groups are boycotting the 
session demanding 100 seats in the council 
the guerrillas fought a nineyear war against the soviets and 
afghan troops 
