<TEXT>
a man who escaped from an ohio prison in 
1940 and spent nearly a halfcentury as a fugitive because ohio 
would not spend money for his extradition has died in boise idaho 
at the age of 72 
charles s biehl died in a veterans administration hospital on 
jan 24 
biehl escaped from the mansfield reformatory while serving a one 
to 20year sentence for cashing a forged 2330 check in richland 
county 
he moved to california where he was arrested periodically in the 
early 1940s by authorities who were forced to release him when ohio 
officials would not pay extradition costs 
he found a job in california and registered for the military 
draft after the japanese attacked pearl harbor biehl was drafted 
into the army and was serving in the aleutian islands off alaska 
when the army learned he was a fugitive from ohio he was given an 
honorable discharge and released 
biehl then went to san francisco married and worked in 
restaurants then moved to boise when he retired 
in 1953 the sheriff of san mateo county calif wrote to 
thenohio gov frank j lausche urging a pardon for biehl saying 
law officers were wasting time and money because ohio kept him on 
the interstate fugitive list 
robert biehl of cuyahoga falls the fugitives brother said the 
state did not try to get his brother back because of the nonviolent 
nature of his offense and the cost of extradition 
biehl never tried to hide either his identity or his 
whereabouts said his brother he kept himself always available 
to be returned to ohio to complete his sentence and deal with the 
escape charge if ohio would come and get him 
</TEXT>
