<TEXT>
a surge in exports of manufactured goods led the nations 1988 
trade deficit to its first improvement of the reagan years 
the narrowing of the trade gap to 13734 billion reported by 
the government friday was well received by the stock market wall 
street rang up its third straight gain lifting the dow jones 
average of 30 industrials 1339 points to 232482 
although the 1988 trade performance matched or even exceeded 
market expectations the dollar showed little reaction friday and 
finished slightly lower against most major currencies 
bond prices finished little changed 
the commerce department reported that exports shot up a dramatic 
268 percent last year to an alltime high of 32222 billion that 
increase supplied much of the economys momentum in 1988 as 
factories hired more workers and expanded production facilities to 
meet the export demand 
however imports rose to a record as well climbing 83 percent 
to 45956 billion the trade deficit is the difference between 
imports and exports 
the deficit declined almost 20 percent from an alltime high of 
17032 billion in 1987 it marked the first improvement since 1980 
the last year of the carter administration in that year the total 
us deficit was a much smaller 314 billion 
through the 1980s the nations trade deficit steadily 
deteriorated posting record imbalances year after year caused in 
part by the huge federal budget deficits which increased demand in 
the economy 
the bush administration which has made reducing the budget 
deficit its no 1 priority said the new trade figures showed the 
imperative need for congress to enact the presidents revised budget 
that document projects a big drop in the deficit while calling 
for a reduction in the capital gains tax as a way of spurring 
investment in new plants and equipment 
